You can do it like this (but in reality is a bad practice).
```java
	  Queue&lt;Integer&gt; ad = new ArrayDeque&lt;&gt;();
	  ad.add(10);
	  ad.add(20);
	  ad.add(30);
	  Iterator&lt;Integer&gt; a = ad.iterator();
	  a.next();
	  a.next();
	  a.remove();
	  System.out.println(ad);
```

However, a queue is a FIFO data structure and is meant to remove elements in the order they were added.  You may want to use a different collection like a `List` implementation.

If you need that kind of behavior you&#39;re looking for something that is not actually a queue, since a queue doesn&#39;t have that behavior.

Have you thought of using something like a `List`?

Anyway, since your `Queue` seems to be a custom class I&#39;ll suppose you could have a `size` method to know how many objects it contains (I see that in your example) and a `push` method to put an element in the queue. In this case, we can remove all elements and put them back as we go along, skipping the second one (and keeping it aside to return it at the end)

    public static Object removesecond(Queue queue){
        Object toReturn;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; queue.size(); i++) {
            Object o = queue.remove();
            if (i != 1) queue.push(o)
            else toReturn = o;
        }
        return toReturn;
    }

Of course this is a naive implementation. You may want to check if you have at least two elements first, check if `queue` is not `null` and define what should happen otherwise.

**EDIT**

In your comment you asked how you can return (so I&#39;ll assume also remove) the second element from the end in case you&#39;re using an `ArrayDequeue`. Of course you can do it the same way as above (using `add` instead of the method I called `push`).

If you want to do it directly you can convert the list to an array (with the `toArray(T[])` method), convert the array to a `List`, remove the unwanted element and keep it aside, clear your queue, put the elements of the `List` back in the `Queue`, return the removed element.

Which is very wasteful and takes a lot more time than the other method, but here it is anyway.

    public static Integer removesecond(ArrayDequeue&lt;Integer&gt; queue){
        Integer toReturn;
        Integer[] arr = queue.toArray(new Integer[0]);
        List&lt;Integer&gt; list = Arrays.asList(arr);
        toReturn = list.remove(list.size() - 2);
        queue.clear();
        queue.addAll(list);
        return toReturn;
    }

